---
Midgaard's charter historians treat the Flood Court Remnants as one of the oldest documented
cases of judicial continuity outlasting its institutional context—a water court that continues
attempting to adjudicate cases for a civic governance structure that no longer exists, using
laws whose current applicability is entirely unclear. The Continuity faction finds this
sympathetic: institutional continuity is preferable to institutional void, even when the
continuing institution has lost its accountability relationships. The Reckoning faction finds
it unsettling for the same reason: institutions that continue operating without accountability
do not become more just over time, regardless of how legitimate their original mandate was.
Midgaard's sealed archive contains several caravan charterer claims referencing Flood Court
water-right records from the pre-collapse period. These claims are legally problematic because
the water-right records, if valid, would establish precedents that predate Midgaard's current
administrative framework. The Continuity faction's archive administration has classified them
as "pending institutional succession review."

