Kowloon's Jade Magistracy has operational interest in the Flood Court Remnants primarily through
the hydraulic engineering records they preserve. Khardaan's cistern verge infrastructure—the
mechanical core that managed water pressure for tomb-sealing operations—represents sophisticated
pre-collapse hydraulic engineering whose operational principles remain relevant for Kowloon's
own water management challenges. The delegation that studied Rakuen's lower terraces during
the last Ledger Vigil had secondary instructions to pursue documentary access to Flood Court
engineering records. The scholar-spirits who hold those records are accessible in principle but
difficult to consult in practice—they engage through judicial protocol rather than archival
protocol, which means access requires framing requests as water-right cases within their
existing procedural framework. Kowloon's delegation attempted this and produced partial results.
The relevant engineering notes are in the Jade Magistracy's restricted technical archive.

