Kiess's scholarly interest in the Flood Court Remnants is legal-historical: the Court represents
a judicial tradition that predates all five current city governments and whose procedural
principles may establish precedents relevant to contemporary water-right disputes. The Syndic
Council's interest is specifically in the Charter of Passage analog the Court enforced—the
principle that water access rights established by original charter cannot be overridden by
subsequent administrative decisions, regardless of the practical resource constraints at the
time of the request. If this principle has continuous legal force through the Flood Court's
surviving records, it would establish the oldest known precedent for the anti-sealed-classification
doctrine Kiess's own charter embodies. Kiess has assigned a scholar-clerk to the formal process
of consulting the Flood Court's surviving spirits through their judicial protocol; the process
is ongoing and has produced two partial records, both relevant to the precedent question.

