---
Deltari Reed Law engages the Flood Court Remnants through the witnessed-measurement tradition:
the Court's water-right records used calibrated measurement systems that the Deltari recognize
as ancestral to their own Reed Law standards. The Court's water-debt ledgers required quarterly
re-measurement of cistern levels against outstanding obligations, with the measurement performed
by a designated court meter-keeper and witnessed by the disputing parties. This is identical
in structure to the co-inspection requirement Deltari Reed Law applies to hydraulic governance.
Deltari archivists studying the Court's records treat the meter-keeper function as the earliest
documented institutionalization of the witnessed-measurement principle they now practice.
The Flood Court's scholar-spirits maintain the measurement records from the pre-collapse period;
Deltari engineers who have consulted them report that the calibration standards are technically
consistent with current best practice, which suggests the underlying engineering principles
were correct even if the governance context collapsed.

