Kethari water-memory preserves knowledge of the desert cistern systems from before the Flood
Court's institutional period. The Khardaan region's aquifer behavior, flood-season patterns,
and drought-cycle signatures are known to Kethari communities whose oral records predate the
necropolis's construction. When the Flood Court's scholar-spirits and the Kethari's water-memory
holders have been brought into consultation—which has happened twice in documented history
through Rakuen's Garden Ledger scholarly network—the result is a layered account: the Kethari
describe the aquifer's natural behavior, and the Flood Court spirits describe how the engineering
modified that behavior and what the modifications required in terms of ongoing management.
The two accounts are consistent in their descriptions of the underlying geology and occasionally
contradictory in their interpretations of what the modifications were designed to achieve.
Kethari hold both accounts simultaneously without requiring resolution.

