Ushabti jurisprudence examines the Flood Court Remnants as a case of genuine judicial authority
operating without a current principal—the closest institutional parallel to the Ushabti's own
situation. The Solar Court that commissioned the Ushabti no longer exists; the Ushabti continue
operating under their autonomous judgment about what their mandate means. The Flood Court's
surviving spirits operate under their last institutional instruction without a current principal
to update or validate those instructions. The difference is that the Ushabti were given
autonomous will to adapt; the Flood Court spirits were not. They are executing fixed judicial
functions in conditions their functions were not designed to address. Ushabti who encounter
Flood Court spirits approach them with a specific respect: they are attempting something that
has not yet failed from their perspective, and the Ushabti know what attempting authority
without a principal looks like from the inside. The consultation protocols the Ushabti use
with Flood Court spirits are more patient and more deferential than those of other races.
